<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-096-058 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 048 074</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  August 1991 v2 n8 p68(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PS/2 upgrades sans IBM. (enhancements to IBM's microcomputer rangefrom third-party vendors)(Forum)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lockwood, Russ.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Products).andO;Product:   IBM PS/2 (Microcomputer) (Product enhancement).andO;Topic:     EnhancementsAccelerator Boards/CardsHard DiskDisk DrivesSingle Inline Memory ModulesUpgradingOEMsThird-Party VendorsMail Order.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Where can you upgrade an IBM PS/2?andP;  You don't have to go to Big Blue.andP;  Somemail-order companies offer non-IBM products to improve PS/2 performance.andM;If you're using the 286-based PS/2 Model 50 or 60, check out the half-dozenoriginal equipment manufacturers who make a daughterboard with a 386SXprocessor, 16K of cache RAM, and a 387 math coprocessor socket.andP;  You pull outthe 286 chip, plug in the daughterboard, and--presto chango--the model 50becomes a 55SX and the model 60 becomes a 65SX.andM;For example, Sigma Data (New London, NH, 800-446-4525) offers a KingstonTechnology daughterboard in 16MHz ($595) and 20MHz ($695) versions.andP;  The PS/2model 50 and 60 recognize the SX chip on the daughterboard, run memorymanagers as on a 386SX computer, and operate in every way as an SX computer.andO;The only difference is a utility program to set up the 16K cache memory.andM;Numerous mail-order companies are also selling 1MB, 2MB, and 4MB singlein-line memory modules (SIMMs) for the PS/2 line.andP;  Like IBM SIMMs, these pluginto a socket on PS/2 models from the 50 to the 95.andP;  The savings can besignificant.andP;  For example, IBM charges $995 for a 4MB SIMM (#34F2933), butmail-order companies charge from about $339 (First Source International,Aliso Viejo, CA, 800-535-5892) to $415 (Sigma Data).andM;Finally, replace that 30MB or 60MB hard drive with a mail-order model.andP;  Oneupgrade option for the model 50 is a Procom 120MB hard drive with a19-millisecond drive and ranges in price from about $799 (MegaHaus, Houston,TX, 800-426-0560) to $929 (MicroSense, Leucadia, CA, 800-544-4252).andM;One caveat in all this concerns the IBM warranty.andP;  Since mail-order companiesare usually not authorized IBM dealers, replacing the PS/2 processor with adaughterboard of your own choosing will void IBM's warranty.andP;  Installing yourown SIMMs or hard drive will not void the warranty.andO;</TEXT></DOC>